Thanks for the comment! Yeah, it's a G#... ish... It's clearly a major chord with the G# as the melody note but the way DF sings it it's a bit bluesy-ish at that spot. Actually, in all three choruses he does not sing it the same way each time. When you arrange a vocal melody for an instrument sometimes things won't match up perfectly, especially a fretted instrument, let a lone a piano, so sometimes you have to decide this note or that. In this case I thought the G# is the most representative, if not quite 100% accurate...

It's kind of like the book "Superchops" by Howard Roberts: straight 1/8's pick every note (repeated notes are ok), but find the tempo you're comfortable doing it for 5 or 10 min straight at, then slowly go up in tempo. I can maybe hang at 120 for a couple minutes! :-)

I find this helps me "get out of my own way", somewhat. For me, improv is mostly about getting into the right frame of mind. When you just have to keep playing, you have to relax and not be tense. It's certainly interesting.

I can usually blow through things fairly well when I am tired. Had an embouchure problem last year from severe muscle fatigue that basically made me rethink my entire approach to the horn. What I've come to now is basically a combination of embouchure adjustments (puckering my lips more in the low range and in general extending my jaw to make my teeth alignment more even) and playing lines that work with my strengths instead of against them.  All of the things I play flow and slot very well for my chops. If I tried to play anything else besides my own personal concept it would probably not go so well. Long story short, this was an intense practice session and my chops were ground up hambruger by this point. As long as Im counter acting with my embouchure adjustments and playing my own harmonic concepts that flow well off my horn, then it will always work. 
(Just to clarify when I say "my own personal concepts" I am actually referring to a system of atonal harmony that I have created for my own playing after a lot of years experimenting) Trust me however good it sounds now, it took a lot of shitty playing on my part to get there! Yo dude souns dope as always :) what are you thinking about when youre playing those lines? do you approach shape and allow notes to fall in a pattern of atonality or are there specific patterns that you practice :)

Hey man! Here is the explanation I gave Kennedy Powers a few weeks when he asked me the same thing on one of my other vids. I hope this helps!

"As for the shapes, its really a form of what I call chromatic sequencing. I take a cell that spans a certain range, come up with a line within that cell, and then shift up in half steps, each time trying to come up with a different melodic shape for each cell. This can be done with a multitutde of different intervals, for example tritones ... C-F#,F-C#-D-G#.... Major or minor thirds C-E,F-A,Bb-D,Eb-G .... C-Eb,E-G etc.... 4ths F-Bb , B-E , F-Bb. This can also be done with differing intervals, for example it doesn't always have to be in a patterns of major 3rds, 4ths, tritones etc... each cell can have a unique interval range that it takes ie C-E,F-Bb-B-F... the idea is that they are always displaced by a half step. The idea is to really come up with a unique shape in each cell which can also mean hovering around the notes within that range for more than one complete rotation or choosing to move on. By choosing to either mimic the interval range of your previous cell , or expand/collapse upon that , you can generate non linear chromatic lines that either grow in range, shrink in range, or hover around the same range each time you shift. "

Nice playing. The most important element of solo guitar is time. Your playing is beautiful because the swing is always there, even when you're silent. A lot of guitar players don't realize that they can keep swinging even in between chords, so they feel they have to mark every beat and they end up stumbling because on guitar it's just not possible to simulate a whole band the entire time. But you've got a wonderful groove going that doesn't depend on the notes you play, so that allows you to play as much or as little as you want without losing the music. From that place there is no limit to what you can do. I look forward to hearing more of your music! Gorgeous vamp at the end too. :-)

Hi Paul Pieper, sounds amazing as always! I just wanted to ask you about your picking technique, are you economy picking, alternate ect? Thanks

Hi Mike! Honestly, I'm not really using either economy or alternate picking here. 
The subject of "picking" is, of course, part of the larger question of articulation, which is a fascinating subject. 

When I started playing jazz, I noticed that across all instruments, there was a sort of consensus around jazz articulation, and how to play eighth notes. There seemed to be a standard, or an ideal, that all the great improvisers had in common, across all instruments. 

The one exception to this - and to my distress, at the time - was "jazz guitar". I noticed that a lot of jazz guitarists seemed to have an articulation that was the result of strict alternate picking, or at least picking almost every note. To my ear, this resulted in eighth-note lines that were not up to the standard of articulation that I was hearing from sax players and piano players. This really bothered me. 

Then I heard John Scofield, who was the first guitarist I heard who played eighth notes that felt as good as Joe Henderson , Sonny Rollins, Bill Evans, or Clifford Brown. It was a revelation for me, and I studied his playing closely and tried to do what he was doing. 

So now, what works for me is to only pick maybe 50% of notes (a very rough approximation). If I'm going to a new string, I have to pick the first note on that string. But I do a lot of hammering and pulling, which helps me get the time feel I want. 

All I'm trying to do is measure up to what I see as a universal ideal of articulation among jazz musicians. Though there is some variation in how the jazz greats play eighth notes, I think there's more in common than there is different. For me, Scofield is the guy who has cracked the code of this articulation as applied to the guitar, so that's how I've tried to approach things. 

Hope that's helpful! Thanks for listening. ðŸ‘

Yea Brandon! I always love hearing you play. Your melodic shapes and contours are excellent. The thing I would recommend for your playing would be more of an intervallic sensibility. One way of doing this would be coming up with a chromatic shape and sequencing it up by a combination of whole steps and half steps, or an interval of your choosing. Its the same type of concept as playing poly pentatonics transposed through a few different keys , except instead of a pentatonic scale you have an actual melodic gesture. Great stuff again man!
Of course max, I remember discussing this with you! I'm a lot more scared to try that kinda thing over a solo performance tho haha
Or rather not scared, just less inclined. Don't wanna confuse myself or the listener lol

I understand, it is a different mindset from the traditional time and changes playing for sure. This idea really stems FROM brass players though and our manipulation of the partial system. Woody, Freddie and Booker were masters at this type of chromatic sequencing. If anything I think it actually generates interest in listeners because at that point they are listening for the shapes of the lines you are playing rather than just if you play this note over that chord. Just my two cents, its definitely something that needs to be done through trial and error ... I can totally agree with that. It also has to do with personal preference and what shapes and contours you feel connect best with your own personal sensibility.

Dave Manley Beautiful Playing man. I was wondering, do the nails on your strumming hand need to be grown out to play like that? If so do you file them or just use a nail clipper. lol I know it random but i would like to work on this stuff and I have no real knowledge on guitar playing.

Jonny, Growing your nails definitely helps project. Natural nail always sounds better than fake nails imop. But, if you can't grow your real nails or having trouble, I do from time to time use the fake glue-on nails you can find a CVS or Walgreens. I am not a fan of acrylic nails, one it ruins your nail-bed. I can't stand the way it sounds, they click on the strings, especially the  treble strings. The fake glue on nails are a little easier on your real nails. I also found that for me shorter nails are better for  tone and control.

Trad jazz holds influence from ragtime, which means that arpeggiations. Try to experiment with arpeggios and melodic mixture.

Also, don't be afraid to syncopate lines, have some fun with the rhythm while still swinging! Start messing around with Blues and pentatonic licks, it's completely  fine to play that stuff in trad jazz!

Were you going for the kind of Balto/amelodic/angular kind of approach?  Nice chops BTW!
Hey Paul, very astute ears. I use a lot of 20th century harmony and things Ive picked up from Indian and various Asian types of music in my improvisation. Eric Dolphy is one of my biggest heroes.
Any suggestions to send me down the rabbit hole in addition to Dolphy?

Oh, I meant Indian and Asian influences :).  I think out refers to, not directly related to the key or chord.  For example, there are some tunes in 7/8 or 11 that don't sound out to me but I definitely don't hear/know a lot of what's going on.  There can be a risk of using "out" concepts/playing to be exclusive and other more negative derivatives of exclusivity at the risk of letting ego get in the way of sincerity/honesty, unfortunately.  That's not what music's about of course; kind of an, "if a tree falls in the forest," thing, I believe.

For me playing "out" has always been a question of what I am playing from note to note, cell to cell, shape to shape, etc... None of these musical ideas really take in the chords or underlying harmonic structure into consideration, then again I wouldn't really consider myself a "jazz improviser" just more of an improviser. The things Im drawing from are  derived massively from a 20th century classical sensibility among other things. Really when it comes down to it,  I sequence chromatic and intervallic cells in differing shapes to generate interest. Being an improviser who has always been active in playing free music, musical shape and contour has always been the thing that appealed to me most.

Man I gotta hit my exercises again lol. Very interesting approach to improv!! Definitely not random by any means. Do you utilize doodle-tongue, perchance?
Also, what are the shapes that you aim for throughout your improv? I'm curious to hear about your thought process, if I may ask!

My doodle was never very strong and I always had trouble tonguing with it across the partials, so no. Mostly everything is just single with a lot of slurs. If its ridiculously fast, say over  320 bpm I usually employ a soft double using reverse syllables ie ... gah-duh-gah-duh-gah . 

As for the shapes, its really a form of what I call chromatic sequencing. I take a cell that spans a certain range, come up with a line within that cell, and then shift up in half steps, each time trying to come up with a different melodic shape for each cell. This can be done with a multitutde of different intervals, for example tritones ... C-F#,F-C#-D-G#.... Major or minor thirds C-E,F-A,Bb-D,Eb-G .... C-Eb,E-G etc.... 4ths F-Bb , B-E , F-Bb. This can also be done with differing intervals, for example it doesn't always have to be in a patterns of major 3rds, 4ths, tritones etc... each cell can have a unique interval range that it takes ie C-E,F-Bb-B-F... the idea is that they are always displaced by a half step. The idea is to really come up with a unique shape in each cell which can also mean hovering around the notes within that range for more than one complete rotation or choosing to move on. By choosing to either mimic the interval range of your previous cell , or expand/collapse upon that , you can generate non linear chromatic lines that either grow in range, shrink in range, or hover around the same range each time you shift. 

I know this is a super long and windy explanation and at first it can seem kind of non sensical, because it is personalized for my own style.
This makes a lot more sense! Fascinating! Do the cells themselves have a specific pattern or an overarching palette that you base the melodic ideas around?
If this question makes any sense lol.

Sort of, I try to use all the notes in every cell as equally as i can before moving on, i want it to sound as non tonal and chromatic as possible. What this really boils down to is finding non repetitive shapes and memorizing what they feel like on the horn.
